   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="vol-2-P_M-d2e7787-person" n="vol-2-P_M-Goliath-1">
               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">גלית<ref corresp="#d2e7777"/>
               </persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Goliath</persName>
               <persName xml:lang="checkme">איגוד/גוליד/גולידו/גולייר/גולירי/גולית<ref corresp="#d185e3"/>
               </persName>
               <persName xml:lang="checkme">/אמי<ref corresp="#d185e11"/>
               </persName>
               <state type="desc">
                  <note>Hananiah (38)’s father</note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>–</note>
               </state>
               <bibl>Gen Rab16:3 (Hyman,Toldoth, 479)</bibl>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>Nickname<ref corresp="#d2e7819"/>
                  </note>
               </state>
               <floruit>3rd-4thC<ref corresp="#d2e7833"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e7791" n="1"> All these
                            versions appear in various mss, see Theodor-Albeck, Bereschit Rabba, 144. This person was obviously not well
                            known, and his name was not stable so that the scribes of the mss were
                            not sure how to write it, see vol. 4, Introduction 5.2.1.1.2.1.1, pp.
                            23-4.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7798" n="2"> So in the printed text, see previous note. This is
                            obviously a scribal “correction,” see vol. 4, Introduction 2.7.2, p. 18.
                            For this name see under Ami
                    S-H/M.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7819" n="3"> Even if this is the said
                            biblical name, it is very unlikely that it was used as a proper name,
                            and see vol. 1, under Goliath (1) B/M, p. 84. On such nicknames see vol.
                            1, Introduction 6.1.1, p. 46.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e7833" n="4"> His son transmits in the name of Joshua
                            (4), who was a student of Rabbi Levi (6), who was a contemporary of
                            Rabbi Yohanan (1), see Introduction 7.4.1.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
